        <section id="faq-506">
            <img alt="" decoding="async" src="/assets/svgs/fern.svg" height="483" width="224" aria-hidden="true" class="cs-fern">
            <div class="cs-container">
                <div class="cs-content">
                    <span class="cs-topper">
                        <span class="cs-topper-dot" aria-hidden="true"></span>
                        <img alt="" decoding="async" src="/assets/svgs/arrow-right.svg" height="10" width="48" aria-hidden="true" class="cs-topper-arrow">
                         FAQ
                    </span>
                    <h2 class="cs-title">Xeriscaping FAQs</h2>
                </div>
                <ul class="cs-faq-list">
                    <li class="cs-faq-item">
                        <details class="cs-faq">
                            <summary class="cs-faq-summary">
                                <span class="cs-faq-question">What is xeriscaping?</span>
                                <span class="cs-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                                    <svg height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24">
                                        <path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"/>
                                    </svg>
                                </span>
                            </summary>
                            <div class="cs-faq-body">
                                <p>Xeriscaping is landscaping built around the seven principles of water-wise design: smart planning, soil prep, plant choice, mulch, efficient irrigation, practical turf use, and low-maintenance care. In Las Cruces, that usually means removing thirsty cool-season turf, replacing it with native and drought-tolerant plants, and putting them on a drip system that uses a fraction of the water a lawn would. Done right, it's a layered, blooming, year-round desert landscape that looks better than a lawn ever did and costs less to keep.</p>
                            </div>
                        </details>
                    </li>
                    <li class="cs-faq-item">
                        <details class="cs-faq">
                            <summary class="cs-faq-summary">
                                <span class="cs-faq-question">How much does xeriscaping cost in Las Cruces?</span>
                                <span class="cs-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                                    <svg height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24">
                                        <path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"/>
                                    </svg>
                                </span>
                            </summary>
                            <div class="cs-faq-body">
                                <p>Xeriscape installation in Las Cruces typically runs $5 to $20 per square foot. A simple design with mulch, gravel paths, and small ground covers lands near $5 per sq ft. Mid-range projects with a full plant install, drip irrigation, edging, and fresh mulch run $10 to $15. Premium installs with boulders, stone pavers, large trees, and water features can reach $20. Most residential conversions in Las Cruces fall between $5,000 and $30,000 total. The on-site consultation is always free.</p>
                            </div>
                        </details>
                    </li>
                    <li class="cs-faq-item">
                        <details class="cs-faq">
                            <summary class="cs-faq-summary">
                                <span class="cs-faq-question">How much water can xeriscaping save?</span>
                                <span class="cs-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                                    <svg height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24">
                                        <path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"/>
                                    </svg>
                                </span>
                            </summary>
                            <div class="cs-faq-body">
                                <p>Most xeriscape conversions cut outdoor water use by 50% or more compared to a traditional turf lawn, and well-designed xeriscapes can reach 70% or higher savings. The biggest gains come from replacing thirsty cool-season turf, switching from sprinklers to drip irrigation, and grouping plants by water need so each zone runs only as long as it has to.</p>
                            </div>
                        </details>
                    </li>
                    <li class="cs-faq-item">
                        <details class="cs-faq">
                            <summary class="cs-faq-summary">
                                <span class="cs-faq-question">What are the disadvantages of xeriscaping?</span>
                                <span class="cs-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                                    <svg height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24">
                                        <path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"/>
                                    </svg>
                                </span>
                            </summary>
                            <div class="cs-faq-body">
                                <p>Two real ones. First, the upfront cost is higher than throwing in turf and a sprinkler. The savings come over years, not months. Second, a xeriscape needs a thoughtful design. A bad xeriscape is a gravel pit with a few struggling plants. Done well, with the right plant palette and a smart drip system, a xeriscape needs less water, less mowing, and less weekly attention than a lawn while looking better year-round.</p>
                            </div>
                        </details>
                    </li>
                    <li class="cs-faq-item">
                        <details class="cs-faq">
                            <summary class="cs-faq-summary">
                                <span class="cs-faq-question">Does xeriscaping increase property value?</span>
                                <span class="cs-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                                    <svg height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24">
                                        <path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"/>
                                    </svg>
                                </span>
                            </summary>
                            <div class="cs-faq-body">
                                <p>In dry climates like Las Cruces, a well-designed xeriscape almost always lifts curb appeal and resale interest. Buyers in southern New Mexico know the math on water bills and summer irrigation rules. A finished, ordinance-compliant xeriscape signals lower utility costs, lower maintenance, and a yard that won't fail in August.</p>
                            </div>
                        </details>
                    </li>
                    <li class="cs-faq-item">
                        <details class="cs-faq">
                            <summary class="cs-faq-summary">
                                <span class="cs-faq-question">Will my xeriscape comply with the Las Cruces watering ordinance?</span>
                                <span class="cs-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                                    <svg height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24">
                                        <path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"/>
                                    </svg>
                                </span>
                            </summary>
                            <div class="cs-faq-body">
                                <p>Yes. Las Cruces enforces a strict outdoor watering schedule (even-numbered addresses water Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday; odd addresses water Wednesday, Friday, Sunday; no watering on Mondays; no watering between 10 a.m. and 6 p.m. from April 1 to September 30). We design every drip system around your address parity and program controllers to those exact rules so you stay in compliance from day one.</p>
                            </div>
                        </details>
                    </li>
                    <li class="cs-faq-item">
                        <details class="cs-faq">
                            <summary class="cs-faq-summary">
                                <span class="cs-faq-question">Can I see your plants growing somewhere before I commit?</span>
                                <span class="cs-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                                    <svg height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24">
                                        <path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"/>
                                    </svg>
                                </span>
                            </summary>
                            <div class="cs-faq-body">
                                <p>Yes. The Las Cruces Utilities demonstration garden at 618 N. Motel Blvd. (open daily 8:30 a.m. to 5 p.m.) is a great preview of native and desert-adapted plants that thrive here. We pull from the same plant palette for most residential xeriscape designs, so you can walk the demo garden, point at what you like, and we'll work it into your plan.</p>
                            </div>
                        </details>
                    </li>
                    <li class="cs-faq-item">
                        <details class="cs-faq">
                            <summary class="cs-faq-summary">
                                <span class="cs-faq-question">How long does a xeriscape install take?</span>
                                <span class="cs-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                                    <svg height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24">
                                        <path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2"/>
                                    </svg>
                                </span>
                            </summary>
                            <div class="cs-faq-body">
                                <p>Most residential xeriscape conversions take one to three weeks of on-site work after the design is approved. Turf removal and soil prep are usually a few days. Hardscape installation (paths, edging, boulders) takes another two to four days. Plant install and drip irrigation usually wraps up in three to five days. Larger or full-property conversions take longer. We give you a calendar week-by-week before any work starts.</p>
                            </div>
                        </details>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>
